  "base_commit": "d07f12b591ed77808de91f0fe1f275339e6d82a9",
  "pr_number": 8509,
  "issue_number": 8505,
  "issue_title": "Networkx Implementation of Leiden Community Detection Algorithm",
  "issue_body": "I have implemented the leiden community detection algorithm within networkx. The original Leiden paper [1] gives pseudocode for the louvain and leiden algorithms side-by-side. My approach was to use the side-by-side pseudocode comparison as a guide to incrementally adapt the networkx implementation of louvain. This required changes in three broad areas:\r\n\r\n    i)   adapting louvain to allow use of a different quality function e.g. Constant-Potts model (CPM)\r\n\r\n    ii)  adapting the _one_level(...) function within networkx louvain to use the logic of the leiden MoveNodesFast function [1]\r\n\r\n    iii) introduce the RefinePartition step from leiden [1]\r\n\r\nNo AI/LLM tools have been used at any stage -- the main reason I undertook this project was to better understand the louvain and leiden algorithms.\r\n\r\n\r\n**Changes to Louvain:**\r\n\r\nIn order to make these changes possible I started with refactoring parts of louvain. In order to implement i) I changed louvain to accept quality_function as parameter with modularity being the default. This allows the louvain algorithm to be run using quality functions other than modularity (e.g. CPM). In order to do this I also had to refactor modularity.\r\n\r\nOne of the challenges when abstracting modularity to more general quality function was that louvain implementation had parts of modularity hard-coded into _one_level(...). This was to calculate the modularity deltas from moving nodes between  communities.\r\n\r\n**Quality Functions:**\r\n\r\nA quality function Q accepts a graph G and a partition P=[A, B, C, D], and returns a numerical value Q(G, P). However, quality functions like modularity and CPM are the sum of values calculated for each community within the partition, which means that computing the effect of moving a node to another can be calculated without computing Q(G, P) in full.\r\n\r\nLet P = [A, B, C, D] be a partition, and suppose we move node u from community A to community B. This gives a new partition P' = [A', B', C, D]. To compute the change in quality from Q(G, P) to Q(G, P'), we only need to calculate the contribution of the terms A and B compared against that of A' and B' because of the property\r\n\r\nQ(G, P) - Q(G, P') = Q(G, [A, B]) - Q(G, [A', B'])\r\n\r\nHowever, the problem with the existing implementation of modularity is that we cannot run modularity(G, [A, B]) because the list of communities does not form a partition of G -- this would raise a NotAPartition exception. Therefore I included another parameter in modularity: allow_partial (set to False by default). If allow_partial=True then the quality function will compute the contribution of the lists of communities, even if these do not form a full partition. This keeps existing behaviour by default of modularity (original tests for louvain and modularity still passing).\r\n\r\nI have implemented the quality function constant_potts_model(...) following [2], which has the same API as the refactored modularity(...), including the allow_partial parameter, and constant_potts_model can be used interchangeably with modularity in both louvain and leiden. Note that I used the formulation of CPM from [2] as it slightly more general than that described in [1]. The formula in [1] requires positive integer node sizes (node_weight). Following [2] the implementation allows for node_weight to be a float (set to 1.0 by default). The node_weight of the aggregated community is the sum of the node_weights of its members.\r\n\r\nI haven't benchmarked performance for the new implementation of louvain against the existing version.\r\n\r\n\r\n**Adapting Louvain to Leiden:**\r\n\r\nThe Leiden implementation is then an adaptation of the refactored louvain code. Like the updated louvain code, leiden can accept quality_function as a parameter, but uses constant_potts_model by default.\r\n\r\nI have created tests for CPM, contant_potts_model(...) I have created a number of tests for Leiden by copying the Louvain tests. I have also included tests that resulting communities are connected.\r\n\r\nFurther tests for Leiden are probably useful. Because the algorithm is non-deterministic, it is difficult to test on known inputs and outputs. The randomness in leiden comes from two parts of the algorithm:\r\n\r\n    1) the order in which nodes are visited\r\n    2) the way communities are chosen from a probability distribution in the _refine_partition(...) stage\r\n\r\nBoth of these are controlled by the same seed, resulting in deterministic behaviour when using a set seed value.\r\n\r\nFrom a quick test against the outputs of leidenalg, the community structures seem similar at the same resolution and theta values, however, more thorough testing may be required to ensure the correctness of this implementation. Overall the results seem to be less stable than leidenalg (greater variance in structure of resulting communities). I don't know why this is, and understanding the difference may come down to looking at implementation details of leidenalg (my initial guess would be it has something to do with the randomness in the order that nodes are visited, but this is not a well-informed view).\r\n\r\n\r\n**TODO:**\r\n\r\n- One test in tests_leiden copied from tests_louvain is still not passing -- test_max_level\r\n- Need to write comprehensive doc strings for leiden_communities and leiden_partitions function\r\n\r\n\r\n[1] \"From Louvain to Leiden: guaranteeing well-connected communities\" Vincent Traag, Ludo Waltman, Nees Jan van Eck\r\n      https://arxiv.org/pdf/1810.08473\r\n\r\n[2] \"Narrow scope for resolution-limit-free community detection\" V.A. Traag, P. Van Dooren, Y. Nesterov\r\n      https://arxiv.org/abs/1104.3083",
  "merged_at": "2026-05-12T17:44:06Z",
